My Seventh SQL Project
Project Overview
My Seventh SQL Project focuses on analyzing and cleaning customer transaction data from an online store.
The goal of this project was to practice data analysis, data cleaning, transaction management, and date analysis while improving database quality and consistency.
During the project, I inspected the dataset structure, corrected data types, handled missing values, standardized text formatting, and analyzed transaction dates. I also practiced working with bit values, transactions, and date functions to better understand how real databases manage and analyze customer data.
This project demonstrates my growing skills in SQL data preparation and database management.

Dataset
The project works with a dataset containing online store customer data.
The table includes information such as:

Customer ID
Gender
State names
Marital status
Customer segment
Transaction dates
Amount spent
Referral indicator

This dataset simulates the kind of customer information used in e-commerce analytics systems.
Project Steps and Analysis

1. Database Creation

The project begins by creating a new SQL database dedicated to this analysis project.
Creating a separate database helps:
Keep projects organized
Prevent interference with other datasets
Practice database management skills

2. Schema Inspection
The first analysis step was checking the structure of the table.
I examined:

Column names
Data types assigned to each column
This step is important because incorrect data types can cause:
calculation errors
storage inefficiency
incorrect query results
By reviewing the schema first, I ensured the dataset was ready for proper analysis.

3. Initial Data Exploration
After reviewing the structure, I examined the full dataset to understand:
what kind of data each column contains
whether any values looked incorrect
if there were missing or inconsistent values
Exploring the data is a critical step in real-world data analysis, because it reveals problems that must be fixed before meaningful analysis can begin.

4. Data Type Correction

One issue discovered in the dataset was that the Amount Spent column contained unnecessary decimal values.
Since customer purchase amounts were intended to be whole numbers, I modified the column’s data type so the database stores the values as integers instead of decimals.
Benefits of this fix:
cleaner numeric data
improved storage efficiency
faster calculations

5. Handling Missing Values
The dataset contained NULL values in several columns.
NULL values can cause problems in calculations and analysis, so I replaced them with default values.
Fixes applied:

Amount spent column
NULL values were replaced with 0
This represents customers who have not spent money
Gender column
Empty values were replaced with 0
This provides a placeholder for missing gender information
Handling missing values is an important part of data cleaning and preparation.

6. Text Standardization

To make the dataset more consistent, I converted certain text fields to lowercase format.
This prevents issues where the same value appears in different formats, such as:
Example problem:

New York
NEW YORK
new york

Standardizing text improves:

filtering accuracy
grouping results
reporting consistency

7. Transaction Management
This project also demonstrates how SQL transactions work.
Transactions allow changes to be controlled safely in a database.
Two transaction actions were practiced:
COMMIT
This permanently saves changes made to the database.
ROLLBACK
This cancels changes and restores the database to its previous state.
Learning transactions is important for data safety and error recovery in real production systems.

8. Date Analysis

The dataset contains customer transaction dates.
I used date functions to analyze order timing.
Finding the Last Day of the Month
I calculated the final day of the month for each transaction date.
This is useful in:

monthly sales reporting
financial summaries
billing cycles
Measuring Order Age
Another analysis calculated how many days ago each order was placed.
This type of calculation helps businesses understand:
customer activity
inactive customers
order recency

9. Working with the BIT Data Type
In this project I practiced working with the bit data type.

A bit column stores binary values:

1 = Yes / True
0 = No / False
This type of column is commonly used for flags such as:
referral indicators
membership status
feature toggles

10. Updating Referral Values

I practiced updating the referral column in multiple ways:
Setting all customers as referred
This demonstrates how to update an entire column.
Updating a specific customer
I modified the referral value for a single customer based on their ID.
Resetting referral values
I also practiced resetting the referral column back to zero.
These exercises helped reinforce how UPDATE operations work.

11. Conditional Updates Based on Date
  
Finally, I applied a condition to update referral values.
Customers whose transaction dates were before 2019 were marked with a referral value of 0.
This type of logic is often used in real systems to:
deactivate old customers
reset expired memberships
clean outdated records
